            <bool>false</bool>
           </property>
           <property name="frameShape">
            <enum>QFrame::Shape::NoFrame</enum>
           </property>
           <property name="text">
            <string>2.2.2 Genome-Wide Association Studies (GWAS) and risk alleles
Genome-Wide Association Studies (GWAS) serve as a comprehensive methodology
for identifying the statistical associations between specific genetic variants and observable
traits or diseases. Unlike traditional candidate-gene approaches that focus
on pre-selected regions of the genome, GWAS involves scanning the entire set of
DNA across large populations. by comparing the genetic profiles of individuals
with a specific nutrition-related condition to a control group, researchers can identify
Single Nucleotide Polymorphisms (SNPs) where the frequency of a particular
allele differs significantly.
The identification of a risk allele within this framework indicates an increased
genetic susceptibility to a condition rather than a definitive diagnosis. In the context
of nutrigenomics, these alleles often signify metabolic predispositions. For example,
specific variants within the FTO gene are frequently associated with higher
Body Mass Index (BMI) or a predisposition toward extreme obesity. The strength
of these associations is quantified as an effect size, which is typically recorded in
3
CHAPTER 2. CLINICAL CONTEXT AND GENOMIC PRINCIPLES
genomic databases as an odds ratio or a beta coefficient. By aggregating the impact
of multiple risk alleles, researchers can develop polygenic risk scores that provide
a comprehensive view of an individual’s genetic landscape, allowing for the design
of personalized dietary interventions based on quantified genetic vulnerabilities</string>
           </property>
           <property name="textFormat">
            <enum>Qt::TextFormat::PlainText</enum>
           </property>
